1 Background

As a statistical consultant working for a real estate investment firm, your task is to develop a model to predict the selling price of a given home in Ames, Iowa. Your employer hopes to use this information to help assess whether the asking price of a house is higher or lower than the true value of the house. If the home is undervalued, it may be a good investment for the firm.

2 Training Data

In order to better assess the quality of the model you will produce, the data have been randomly divided into three separate pieces: a training data set, a testing data set, and a validation data set.

2.1 Part 1 - Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

When you first get your data, it’s very tempting to immediately begin fitting models and assessing how they perform. However, before you begin modeling, it’s absolutely essential to explore the structure of the data and the relationships between the variables in the data set.

Do a detailed EDA of the ames_train data set, to learn about the structure of the data and the relationships between the variables in the data set (refer to Introduction to Probability and Data, Week 2, for a reminder about EDA if needed). Your EDA should involve creating and reviewing many plots/graphs and considering the patterns and relationships you see.

After you have explored completely, submit the three graphs/plots that you found most informative during your EDA process, and briefly explain what you learned from each (why you found each informative).

2.1.1 BOX Plots

ggplot(data=ames_train, aes(x=Neighborhood, y=log(price))) + geom_boxplot() + labs(title = "Real estate prices in Ames, Iowa", x= "Neighborhood", y= "log(price)") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, hjust=1))

It is believed that the most important determinant of price in real estate is the location of a property. Hence, a boxlplot was created to visualize if certain locations show higher price of house property than the others. The boxplot does not suggest any systematic difference in the estate prices. Hence, there are other variables which influence the price of a real estate. Also, the boxlplot suggests that the distribution of the prices is right-skewed.

2.2 Part 2 - Development and assessment of an initial model, following a semi-guided process of analysis

2.2.1 Section 2.1 An Initial Model

In building a model, it is often useful to start by creating a simple, intuitive initial model based on the results of the exploratory data analysis. (Note: The goal at this stage is not to identify the “best” possible model but rather to choose a reasonable and understandable starting point. Later you will expand and revise this model to create your final model.

Based on your EDA, select at most 10 predictor variables from “ames_train” and create a linear model for price (or a transformed version of price) using those variables. Provide the R code and the summary output table for your model, a brief justification for the variables you have chosen, and a brief discussion of the model results in context (focused on the variables that appear to be important predictors and how they relate to sales price).

Based on my EDA, following predictors will be used to arrive at a parsimonious model using

init_model <- lm(log(price) ~ log(Lot.Area) + MS.SubClass + Overall.Qual + Overall.Cond + Heating.QC + Year.Built + House.Style + Neighborhood + Exterior.1st, data = ames_train)

2.2.2 Sction 2.2 Model Selection

Now either using BAS another stepwise selection procedure choose the “best” model you can, using your initial model as your starting point. Try at least two different model selection methods and compare their results. Do they both arrive at the same model or do they disagree? What do you think this means?

Let us use AIC model selection method to arrive at a parsimonious model.

init_model_AIC <- stepAIC(init_model, direction = 'backward', trace = FALSE)

Next, let us modify the selection method to BIC model selection and compare the two results

init_model_BIC <- stepAIC(init_model, direction = 'backward', k=log(nrow(ames_train)), trace = FALSE)

The results of model selection are different for the two methods. This is because AIC imposes a higher penalty on the adjusted R-squared value whereas BIC imposes a higher penalty for more number of predictors.

Since the objective of this assignment is to predict the house property prices, we will use AIC method to arrive at a parsimonious model.

2.2.4 Section 2.4 Initial Model RMSE

You can calculate it directly based on the model output. Be specific about the units of your RMSE (depending on whether you transformed your response variable). The value you report will be more meaningful if it is in the original units (dollars).

predict_init <- exp(predict(init_model_AIC, ames_train))
resid_init <- ames_train$price - predict_init
rmse_init <- sqrt(mean(resid_init^2))
rmse_init
## [1] 33794.63

The RMSE was calculated based on AIC model output. Since we used log-transformed price in the initial model, the RMSE comes out to be 33794.6 dollars.

2.2.5 Section 2.5 Overfitting

The process of building a model generally involves starting with an initial model (as you have done above), identifying its shortcomings, and adapting the model accordingly. This process may be repeated several times until the model fits the data reasonably well. However, the model may do well on training data but perform poorly out-of-sample (meaning, on a dataset other than the original training data) because the model is overly-tuned to specifically fit the training data. This is called “overfitting.” To determine whether overfitting is occurring on a model, compare the performance of a model on both in-sample and out-of-sample data sets. To look at performance of your initial model on out-of-sample data, you will use the data set ames_test.

Use your model from above to generate predictions for the housing prices in the test data set. Are the predictions significantly more accurate (compared to the actual sales prices) for the training data than the test data? Why or why not? Briefly explain how you determined that (what steps or processes did you use)?

The following errors occured while predicting the values from test dataset: factor House.Style has new levels 2.5Fin factor Neighborhood has new levels Landmrk factor Exterior.1st has new levels AsphShn Since the no. of observations is very small, we will eliminate these observations from our test model

ames_test <- ames_test %>% filter(House.Style != '2.5Fin') %>% filter(Neighborhood != 'Landmrk') %>% filter(Exterior.1st != 'AsphShn')
predict_test <- exp(predict(init_model_AIC, ames_test))
resid_test <- ames_test$price - predict_test
rmse_test <- sqrt(mean(resid_test^2))
rmse_test
## [1] 31670.79

The value of RMSE decreases to 31670.79 dollars for out-of-sample prediction. This indicates that the model predicts the values of prices for test dataset better than the training dataset. Hence, there does not appear to be a case of overfilling.

3.2 Transformation

Did you decide to transform any variables? Why or why not? Explain in a few sentences.

Yes. The model uses log-transformations of variables price and Lot.Area. This is because with a marginal increase in the lot area (square footage), the price of the real estate property goes up. Thus, there is an exponential relationship between the Lot.Area and price.

In order to fit a linear model to the Lot.Area and price, we have to log-transform these variables. The graph below suggests the result of transformation. There is clearly a better linear fit with log-transformation

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

ggplot(data=ames_train, aes(x=Lot.Area, y=price)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm") + labs(title = "Price variation with area", x="lot area", y="price")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data=ames_train, aes(x=log(Lot.Area), y=log(price))) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm") + labs(title = "Log-transformed Price variation with log-transformed area", x="log(lot area)", y="log(price)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

3.3 Variable Interaction

Did you decide to include any variable interactions? Why or why not? Explain in a few sentences.

The number of variables used in this model are 9. If we decide to include any interactions, the number of variables to be fitted in the linear model will increase by 9 x 8 = 72. Thus, I have decided not to include any variable interactions.

3.4 Variable Selection

What method did you use to select the variables you included? Why did you select the method you used? Explain in a few sentences.

AIC was used in model selection. This is because a frequentist approach with AIC to linear regression will give more penalty to adjusted R-squared value. Since the goal of the assignment is to predict the price of the property, this method is superior to BIC which uses Bayesian reasoning (more penalty to the no. of variables included in the model)

3.5 Model Testing

How did testing the model on out-of-sample data affect whether or how you changed your model? Explain in a few sentences.

RMSE was lower for out-of-sample prediction. This suggests that there was no overfitting in the initial model. Thus, final model does not vary from the initial model.

4.4 Final Model Validation

Testing your final model on a separate, validation data set is a great way to determine how your model will perform in real-life practice.

You will use the “ames_validation” dataset to do some additional assessment of your final model. Discuss your findings, be sure to mention: * What is the RMSE of your final model when applied to the validation data? * How does this value compare to that of the training data and/or testing data? * What percentage of the 95% predictive confidence (or credible) intervals contain the true price of the house in the validation data set? * From this result, does your final model properly reflect uncertainty?

ames_validation <- ames_validation %>% filter(House.Style != '2.5Fin') %>% filter(Neighborhood != 'Landmrk') %>% filter(Exterior.1st != 'AsphShn') %>% filter(Exterior.1st != 'CBlock') %>% filter(Exterior.1st != 'PreCast')
predict_valid <- exp(predict(init_model_AIC, ames_validation))
resid_valid <- ames_validation$price - predict_valid
rmse_valid <- sqrt(mean(resid_valid^2))
rmse_valid
## [1] 28177.37

The RMSE for validation dataset turns out to be 28177 dollars. This is lower than both training and test dataset values, suggesting that no overfitting was done.

predict_CI <- exp(predict(init_model_AIC, ames_validation, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95))
coverage.prob.full <- mean(ames_validation$price > predict_CI[,"lwr"] & ames_validation$price < predict_CI[,"upr"])
coverage.prob.full
## [1] 0.9748677

The coverage probability of the final model is 97.47%. Thus, the model is good at predicting almost 97% of all the values in the validation dataset.

5 Conclusion

Provide a brief summary of your results, and a brief discussion of what you have learned about the data and your model.

This was a complex dataset for real estate property prices in Ames, Iowa. Out of a total 81 variables, based on intuition and EDA, a maximum of 9 variables were chosen to predict the house prices. Some of the variables were log-transformed to give a better linear fit.

The linear model had an adjusted R-squared value of 0.834 based on AIC backward model selection method. The comparison of RMSE values between training and test data set suggests that there is no possible overfitting in the linear model.

The linear model was able to predict over 97% of values in the validation dataset. Thus, the model is a very good predictor of real-life real estate prices.
